==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/wer/}}

===Etymology===
From Proto-Germanic ''*wirāz'', from Proto-Indo-European ''*wīrō-'' ('[[freeman]]'). Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''wer'', Old Saxon ''wer'', Old High German ''wer'', Old Norse [[verr]], Gothic [[𐍅𐌴𐍂]]. The PIE root is also the source of Latin [[vir]], Old Irish [[fer]] (Welsh [[gwr]]), Baltic ''*wira-'' (Lithuanian [[viras|vīras]]).
====Noun====
'''wer''' {{m}} (pl. ''weras'')

# [[man]], [[husband]]

===Etymology===
From the verb ''[[werian]]''
====Noun====
'''wer'''

# [[weir]]

